text.tspan: The HSEQA Department and Manning office shall prepare annual training plans in consultation HR & Crew and TechnicalDepartments covering mandatory, identified and preferred training.The Manning office shall monitor the programs, ensure that required training is carried out within the planned time frame and report toHR & Crew Department.Superintendents shall actively impart training during their stints on board.Onboard training shall be supervised and closely monitored by the Master.4.20.3IDENTIFICATION OF TRAINING NEEDSMaster in consultation with the Heads of Department shall identify the training needs in support of the ‘Safety Management System’ of the staff on board. This shallbe reported in the appraisal system in PHOENIX.The training needs shall be given priority and shall be resolved at the earliest. Master will arrange training on board as required.The Manning offices shall be responsible to plan and ensure that Training needs identified have been suitable addressed. At the time of being re-assigned the Crewmembers’ Appraisals and Identified Training needs in PHOENIX shall be inspected by relevant staff in the Manning Office and additional shore based trainingprovided as deemed necessary.The training shall as far as possible be completed prior to the seafarer joining the vessel but not later than the following assignment if training requirement is noturgent and circumstances do not permit.4.20.4TRAINING, BRIEFING AND FAMILIARISATIONTraining, Briefing and Familiarisation is carried out through the following processes:a) Pre-assignment Training.Prior to being approved for joining a vessel the seafarer shall undergo the identified Training courses / modules which are applicableto him.b) Pre Joining Briefing.New Masters and Chief Engineers and ex hands (when so required) will be routed via office for briefing prior joining the vessel.Some Charterers may require Master and Chief Engineers to also be briefed at their offices.Briefing of Masters and Chief Engineers may be carried out by video conferencing when, due to time constraints, they are not able to be briefed in person.c) Onboard Familiarisation and Training. 1) All seafarers shall be given onboard familiarisation training upon joining a vessel, pertinent to that vessel. It shall be theresponsibility of the Master and respective head of the department to impart the necessary training. – Ref Vessel Operation ManualSection 5 2) The Onboard Training shall be carried out and records maintained by using Phoenix Training Module. RefVessel OperationManual Section 5. 3) Potential emergency drills, likely to be involved with the ship, shall be practised for which the Master of each vessel shall beresponsible to impart necessary training to the staff and to specify the period between which such drills are to be held. Such recordsshall also be maintained by the Master. 4) Besides above a training record book covering all aspects of the vessel's operation shall be issued by the company to each cadetjoining a vessel and the Chief officer shall be responsible to assess his performance at the period specified.4.20.5TRAINING RECORDSRelevant training records shall be maintained on board and ashore. Effectiveness of individual training is to be obtained at the end ofeach course. In addition on board evaluation is to be conducted by the Master/ Chief Engineer and feedback given to training institutefor analysing the effectiveness of training.4.20.6DEBRIEFINGForm CR 15 (Senior Officers De-Briefing/ Feedback form) is to be used for this purpose.4.20.7SHORE ASSIGNMENTS FOR SEAGOING STAFFThe company has a structured program to allow selected Masters and Chief Engineers to go through Shore assignments. Thecandidates undergo 3 days of training ashore and are then assigned to Technical/ Crew/ Operations/ HSEQA department for a periodof approximately 4 weeks.4.20.8SIMULATOR TRAINING FOR ANCHOR HANDLING OPERATIONSAnchor handling operations are highly specialised and critical operations and it is essential that key staff onboard are competent andadequately trained / experienced in anchor handling operations. The company seeks to use Simulator Training to supplementshipboard experience as appropriate.The table below specifies the criteria for key staff to undergo Simulator Training in Anchor handling:Advanced AHT Simulator trainingBasic AHT Simulator training1) Chief Officer prior promotion to Master.2) Second Engineer prior promotion to Chief Engineer.3) Master with less than 24 months experience on AHTS vessels.4) CE with less than 24 months experience on AHTS vessels.1) Bosun, with less than 24 months experience on AHTS vessels.2) Able Seaman prior promotion to Bosun.
